999|website=afltables.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#cfc;\"\n|FW2\n| align=\"left\" |{{leagueicon|Sydney|16}} [[Sydney Roosters|Sydney City Roosters]]\n|18 \u2013 28\n| align=\"left\" |{{leagueicon|St George Illawarra|16}} [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]]\n|11 September\n|[[Sydney Football Stadium]]\n|[[Bill Harrigan]]\n|31,506\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://afltables.com/rl/scorers/games/1999/199909110929.html|title=Rugby League Tables / St George Illawarra 28 v Sydney City 18 / Semi Final, 1999|website=afltables.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#cfc;\"\n|FW3\n| align=\"left\" |{{leagueicon|Cronulla|16}} [[Cronulla-Sutherland Sharks]]\n|8 \u2013 24\n| align=\"left\" |{{leagueicon|St George Illawarra|16}} [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]]\n|19 September\n|[[Stadium Australia]]\n|Steve Clark\n|51,827\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://afltables.com/rl/scorers/games/1999/199909190729.html|title=Rugby League Tables / St George Illawarra 24 v Cronulla 8 / Preliminary Final, 1999|website=afltables.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|- style=\"text-align:center; background:#FFCFCF;\"\n|[[1999 NRL Grand Final|GF]]\n| align=\"left\" |{{leagueicon|Melbourne|16}} [[Melbourne Storm]]\n|20 \u2013 18\n| align=\"left\" |{{leagueicon|St George Illawarra|16}} [[St. George Illawarra Dragons]]\n|26 September\n|[[Stadium Australia]]\n|[[Bill Harrigan]]\n|107,999\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://afltables.com/rl/scorers/games/1999/199909262729.html|title=Rugby League Tables / Melbourne 20 v St George Illawarra 18 / Grand Final, 1999|website=afltables.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n<references />{{St. George Illawarra Dragons}}{{1999 in rugby league}}\n[[Category:St. George Illawarra Dragons]]\n[[Category:St. George Illawarra Dragons seasons]]\n[[Category:1999 in rugby league by club]]\n", "name_user": "WDM10", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1999_St._George_Illawarra_Dragons_season"}
{"title_page": "University Institute of Information Technology, Himachal Pradesh University", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date = October 2014}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name = University Institute of Technology (UIT) Shimla\n| native_name = \n| latin_name = \n| image_name = \n| motto = Eyes of Knowledge Seeth\n| established = 2000\n| endowment = \n| faculty = \n| chancellor = Bandaru Dattatreya\n| vice_chancellor = Prof. Sikander Kumar<ref name=\"Professor Sikander Kumar 26th VC at HPU - Times of India\">https://timesofindia.com/home/education/news/professor-sikander-kumar-26th-vc-at-hpu/amp_articleshow/65258915.cms</ref>\n| dean = \n| director = Prof. (Dr.) P. L. Sharma <ref name=\"uiit website\">[http://www.uiit.ac.in www.uiit.ac.in]</ref>\n| doctoral = \n| coor = {{Coord|31.1117|77.1401|type:edu_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| city = [[Shimla]]\n| state = [[Himachal Pradesh]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| campus = [[Urban areas|Urban]]\n| free_label = Acronym\n| free = UIT\n| colors = \n| colours = \n| mascot = \n| affiliations = [[Himachal Pradesh University]]\n| website = [http://www.uiit.ac.in www.uiit.ac.in]\n}}\n\n'''University Institute of Technology''', Himachal Pradesh ('''UIT''') (erstwhile '''University Institute of Information Technology''', Himachal Pradesh ('''UIIT''') is in the [[Himachal Pradesh University]]) campus at [[Summer Hill, Shimla|Summerhill]], [[Shimla]], India. It started functioning on 11 September 2000.\n\nUIT has been producing professional leaders in the field of information technology, as well as enhancing technological strength of the region and the country. Well known for its B.Tech in Information Technology programme throughout [[India]], the institute benefits from close collaborations with the IT industry.\n\n==Facilities==\n\n===Internet facility===\nThe university has been provided by [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] a leased line of 50 Mbit/s (1:1) dedicated bandwidth as a part of UGC infonet for Higher Education. UIIT is a member of the Campus Wide Optical Fibre Network on which Internet facility is available on 22\u00d76 basis.\n\n===Campus===\nThe campus has 14\u00d76 Wi-Fi connectivity and  banking facilities. Currently classes are held in the new UIT Building, Silver Wood Estate, Near Police Station, Summerhill.\n\n==Placements==\nPlacement of the students is of major concern to the institute. For this purpose, a full-time placement cell under a faculty member has been created to liaison among the students and prospective employers and to keep a watchful eye on the emerging trends and future needs of the industry.\n\nThe institute has a good track record of placements with students placed in companies like [[Infosys]], GlobalLogic, Sapient, [[Tata Consultancy Services]], Accenture, Cognizant, Oracle, [[Mahindra Satyam|Satyam]], [[Wipro]], [[Tech Mahindra]], [[NexTag]], Impetus, Perot systems, and [[IBM]].\n\n==Extra-curricular==\n\nThe institute organizes events for the all-round development of the students. The biggest event is UTKARSH, a four-day inter-college festival in which colleges from in and around the state are invited to participate. The fest is conducted by Engineering Technology Students Association (ETSA) which has a president, vice president, finance secretary, cultural secretary, general secretary and joint secretary in the Governing Body. It is the only event of its kind on the campus which takes place at three venues simultaneously with 1500 to 2000 students. Other events include inter-college sports competition.\n\n==Alumni==\nStudents from UIT work in prestigious companies like Google, Facebook, Juniper Networks, Royal Dutch Shell, Adobe, Microsoft, and Walmart Labs.\n\n==Change of Name==\nOn 28 February 2020, the name of University Institute of Information Technology(UIIT) changed to University Institute of Technology(UIT) due to addition of other engineering branches.<ref>http://uiit.ac.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Notification-UIT-Name-Change.pdf</ref>\n== See also ==\n* [[Himachal Pradesh University]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Himachal Pradesh topics}}\n{{Universities in Himachal Pradesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Institute Of Information Technology, Himachal Pradesh University}}\n[[Category:Universities in Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Himachal Pradesh University]]\n[[Category:Education in Shimla]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{refimprove|date = October 2014}}\n{{Infobox University\n| name = University Institute of Technology (UIT) Shimla\n| native_name = \n| latin_name = \n| image_name = \n| motto = Eyes of Knowledge Seeth\n| established = 2000\n| endowment = \n| faculty = \n| chancellor = Bandaru Dattatreya\n| vice_chancellor = Prof. Sikander Kumar<ref name=\"Professor Sikander Kumar 26th VC at HPU - Times of India\">https://timesofindia.com/home/education/news/professor-sikander-kumar-26th-vc-at-hpu/amp_articleshow/65258915.cms</ref>\n| dean = \n| director = Prof. (Dr.) P. L. Sharma <ref name=\"uiit website\">[http://www.uiit.ac.in www.uiit.ac.in]</ref>\n| doctoral = \n| coor = {{Coord|31.1117|77.1401|type:edu_region:IN|display=inline,title}}\n| city = [[Shimla]]\n| state = [[Himachal Pradesh]]\n| country = [[India]]\n| campus = [[Urban areas|Urban]]\n| free_label = Acronym\n| free = UIT\n| colors = \n| colours = \n| mascot = \n| affiliations = [[Himachal Pradesh University]]\n| website = [http://www.uiit.ac.in www.uiit.ac.in]\n}}\n\n'''University Institute of Technology''', Himachal Pradesh ('''UIT''') (erstwhile '''University Institute of Information Technology''', Himachal Pradesh ('''UIIT''') is in the [[Himachal Pradesh University]]) campus at [[Summer Hill, Shimla|Summerhill]], [[Shimla]], India. It started functioning on 11 September 2000.\n\nUIT has been producing professional leaders in the field of information technology, as well as enhancing technological strength of the region and the country. Well known for its B.Tech in Information Technology programme throughout [[India]], the institute benefits from close collaborations with the IT industry.\n\n==Facilities==\n\n===Internet facility===\nThe university has been provided by [[University Grants Commission (India)|University Grants Commission]] a leased line of 50 Mbit/s (1:1) dedicated bandwidth as a part of UGC infonet for Higher Education. UIIT is a member of the Campus Wide Optical Fibre Network on which Internet facility is available on 22\u00d76 basis.\n\n===Campus===\nThe campus has 14\u00d76 Wi-Fi connectivity and  banking facilities. Currently classes are held in the new UIT Building, Silver Wood Estate, Near Police Station, Summerhill.\n\n==Placements==\nPlacement of the students is of major concern to the institute. For this purpose, a full-time placement cell under a faculty member has been created to liaison among the students and prospective employers and to keep a watchful eye on the emerging trends and future needs of the industry.\n\nThe institute has a good track record of placements with students placed in companies like [[Infosys]], GlobalLogic, Sapient, [[Tata Consultancy Services]], Accenture, Cognizant, Oracle, [[Mahindra Satyam|Satyam]], [[Wipro]], [[Tech Mahindra]], [[NexTag]], Impetus, Perot systems, and [[IBM]].\n\n==Extra-curricular==\n\nThe institute organizes events for the all-round development of the students. The biggest event is UTKARSH, a four-day inter-college festival in which colleges from in and around the state are invited to participate. The fest is conducted by Engineering Technology Students Association (ETSA) which has a president, vice president, finance secretary, cultural secretary, general secretary and joint secretary in the Governing Body. It is the only event of its kind on the campus which takes place at three venues simultaneously with 1500 to 2000 students. Other events include inter-college sports competition.\n\n==Alumni==\nStudents from UIT work in prestigious companies like Google, Facebook, Juniper Networks, Royal Dutch Shell, Adobe, Microsoft, and Walmart Labs.\n\n==Change of Name==\nOn 28 February 2020, the name of University Institute of Information Technology(UIIT) changed to University Institute of Technology(UIT) due to addtion of other engineering branches.<ref>http://uiit.ac.in/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Notification-UIT-Name-Change.pdf</ref>\n== See also ==\n* [[Himachal Pradesh University]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Himachal Pradesh topics}}\n{{Universities in Himachal Pradesh}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:University Institute Of Information Technology, Himachal Pradesh University}}\n[[Category:Universities in Himachal Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Himachal Pradesh University]]\n[[Category:Education in Shimla]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_Institute_of_Information_Technology,_Himachal_Pradesh_University"}
{"title_page": "Greater China", "text_new": "{{short description|Region with commercial and cultural ties to the Han Chinese}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s=\u5927\u4e2d\u534e\n|t=\u5927\u4e2d\u83ef\n|p=D\u00e0 Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1\n|bpmf=\u3109\u311a\u02cb \u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u3128\u311a\u02ca\n|j=daai6 zung1 waa4<!--For Hong Kong and Macau-->\n|poj=T\u0101i Tiong-h\u00f4a\n|order=st}}\n<!--[[File:Greater China.GIF|300px|thumb|Approximate range map of Greater China, which includes Mainland China, Macau, Hong Kong and Taiwan]]-->\n\n'''Greater China''' is a controversial geopolitical term. When used in business and academia, it usually encompasses [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], [[Taiwan]] and sometimes may include other [[overseas Chinese]] communities, notably [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"Journal1\">{{Cite journal|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal = Comparative Education|volume = 52|pages = 26\u201343|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|year = 2016|quote=This term can be narrowly defined as referring to a geographic concept that consists of the People's Republic of China, the Republic of China, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and the Macau Special Administrative Region, where ethnic Chinese comprise the majority of the population. In this sense, the term is used to describe the ethnic and the associated political, economic and cultural ties among these Chinese societies (Harding 1993; Cheung 2013).}}</ref><ref name=\"Journal2\">{{Cite journal|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|year=2016|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal=Comparative Education|volume=52|pages=26\u201343|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|quote=However, some analysts see the Greater China concept as a way to summarise \u2018the linkages among the fair-flung international Chinese community\u2019, thereby incorporating Singapore and overseas Chinese communities in their usage of the term (Harding 1993, 660; also see Wang 1993).}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harding|first=Harry|date=December 1993|title=The Concept of \"Greater China\": Themes, Variations and Reservations*|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/china-quarterly/article/concept-of-greater-china-themes-variations-and-reservations/FAED34F84F7A8CF25CB3328991218293|journal=The China Quarterly|language=en|volume=136|pages=660\u2013686|doi=10.1017/S030574100003229X|issn=1468-2648|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\n\n===Commercial usage===\n\n[[Multinational corporation|Multinational corporations]] frequently use the term to name their regional [[Corporate headquarters|headquarters]]. For example, [[Procter & Gamble|P&G]] uses it to name its regional headquarter in [[Guangzhou]] that also operates in Hong Kong and [[Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web |title=P&G in Greater China |url=https://www.pgcareers.com/location-greaterchina |website=www.pgcareers.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] uses it for its regional headquarter in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news |title=Isabel Ge Mahe named Apple's managing director of Greater China |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/07/isabel-ge-mahe-named-apple-managing-director-of-greater-china/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Apple Newsroom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mickle |first1=Andrew Dowell and Tripp |title=Apple Closes All Its Stores Outside China Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-closes-all-its-stores-outside-china-over-coronavirus-11584172214 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Academic usage===\n\n[[Universities]] among other [[research institutions]] such as [[Columbia University]] use the term for studies of the region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater China - Weatherhead East Asian Institute |url=http://weai.columbia.edu/research/regions/china-region/ |website=weai.columbia.edu |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Political usage===\nThe term is often used to avoid invoking sensitivities over the [[political status of Taiwan]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\"/>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nFormer [[PRC Foreign Minister|Foreign Minister of China]] [[Wu Xueqian]] claimed in 1995 that China rejects the idea of a \"Greater China economic circle\" as it would never resort to economic expansionism or be involved in dividing the world.<ref name=\"He2001\">{{cite book|author=Henry Yuhuai He|title=Dictionary of the Political Thought of the People's Republic Of China|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=O6ac30QVU-4C&pg=PA48|accessdate=5 April 2020|year=2001|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-0569-6|pages=48}}</ref>\n\nMany Taiwanese don't believe themselves to be a part of greater China as it gives impression that Taiwan is part of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan Business TOPICS 2018\">{{cite web | title=Does Taiwan Belong In \"Greater China?\" | website=Taiwan Business TOPICS | date=2018-05-16 | url=https://topics.amcham.com.tw/2018/05/does-taiwan-belong-in-greater-china/ | access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"JSTOR\">{{cite journal | jstor=2620593 | title=China and Taiwan: Not Yet 'Greater China' | last1=Crane | first1=George T. | journal=International Affairs (Royal Institute of International Affairs 1944-) | year=1993 | volume=69 | issue=4 | pages=705\u2013723 }}</ref><ref name=\"National Sun Yat-Sen University\">{{cite web | author=Jeanette Ka-yee Yuen | title=The Myth of Greater China? Hong Kong as a prototype of Taiwan for Unification | website=Taiwan in Comparative Perspective | date=2020-03-22 | url=http://archive.is/Jgq9F | access-date=2020-03-22 | issn=1752-7732 |  others=Taiwan Research Programme, London School of Economics}}</ref>\n\nFor some Asians{{who|date=March 2020}}, the term is a reminder of the \"[[Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere]]\", a euphemism for the region controlled by [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japan]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite journal\n  | last = Shambaugh\n  | first = David\n  | title = Introduction: The Emergence of 'Greater China'\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 654\n  | date = December 1993}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\n<!--[[File:China Proper 1944.png|thumb|left|250px|The map of \"China\" in the 1944 American [[propaganda film]] ''[[The Battle of China]]'', distinguishing \"[[China proper]]\" from [[Manchuria]], \"Mongolia\" (here [[Pan-Mongolism|Greater Mongolia]] including [[Mongolia|the present country]], the [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], and [[Tuva]]), [[Xinjiang|Sinkiang]], and [[Tibet]].]]\nThe term has been used for a long time, but with differing scope and connotations.-->\n\nIn the 1930s [[George Cressey]] used it to refer to the entire [[Qing Dynasty|Chinese Empire]], as opposed to [[China proper]].<ref name=\"Harding\">{{cite journal\n  | first = Harry\n  | last = Harding\n  | title = The Concept of 'Greater China': Themes, Variations and Reservations\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 660\u2013686\n  | date = December 1993| volume = 136\n | doi = 10.1017/S030574100003229X\n }}\n</ref> Usage by the United States on government maps in the 1940s as a political term included territories [[History of the Republic of China|claimed by the Republic of China]] that were part of the previous empire, or geographically to refer to topographical features associated with China that may or may not have lain entirely within Chinese political borders.<ref name=\"Harding\" /> \n\nThe concept began to appear again in Chinese-language sources in the late 1970s, referring the growing commercial ties between the mainland and Hong Kong, with the possibility of extending these to Taiwan, with perhaps the first such reference being in a Taiwanese journal ''Changqiao'' in 1979.<ref name=\"Harding\" />{{verification needed|date=March 2020}} \n\nThe English term subsequently re-emerged in the 1980s to refer to the growing economic ties between the regions as well as the possibility of political unification.<ref name=\"Harding\" /> It is not an institutionalized entity such as the [[European Union|EU]] or [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]]. The concept is a generalization to group several markets seen to be closely linked economically and does not imply [[sovereignty]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\">{{cite book  | first = Tilman  | last = Aretz  | title = The greater China factbook  | publisher = Taiwan Elite Press  | location = Taipei  | year = 2007  | url = http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | isbn = 978-986-7762-97-9 <!--9867762975-->  | oclc = 264977502  | url-status = live  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090131200221/http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | archivedate = 2009-01-31  }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Hong Kong|Taiwan|Singapore}}\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Adoption of Chinese literary culture]]\n* [[Bamboo network]]\n* [[East Asian cultural sphere]]\n* [[History of China]]\n* [[List of tributaries of China]]\n* [[Nine-dash line]]\n* [[Sinophone]]\n* [[Greater India]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese nationalism]]\n[[Category:Country classifications|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Cross-Strait relations]]\n[[Category:Cultural regions|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Geography of China]]\n[[Category:Historical regions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Region with commercial and cultural ties to the Han Chinese}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s=\u5927\u4e2d\u534e\n|t=\u5927\u4e2d\u83ef\n|p=D\u00e0 Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1\n|bpmf=\u3109\u311a\u02cb \u3113\u3128\u3125 \u310f\u3128\u311a\u02ca\n|j=daai6 zung1 waa4<!--For Hong Kong and Macau-->\n|poj=T\u0101i Tiong-h\u00f4a\n|order=st}}\n<!--[[File:Greater China.GIF|300px|thumb|Approximate range map of Greater China, which includes Mainland China, Macau, Hong Kong and Taiwan]]-->\n\n'''Greater China''' is a controversial geopolitical term. When used in business and academia, it usually encompasses [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], [[Taiwan]] and sometimes may include other [[overseas Chinese]] communities, notably [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"Journal1\">{{Cite journal|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal = Comparative Education|volume = 52|pages = 26\u201343|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|year = 2016|quote=This term can be narrowly defined as referring to a geographic concept that consists of the People's Republic of China, the Republic of China, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and the Macau Special Administrative Region, where ethnic Chinese comprise the majority of the population. In this sense, the term is used to describe the ethnic and the associated political, economic and cultural ties among these Chinese societies (Harding 1993; Cheung 2013).}}</ref><ref name=\"Journal2\">{{Cite journal|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|year=2016|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal=Comparative Education|volume=52|pages=26\u201343|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|quote=However, some analysts see the Greater China concept as a way to summarise \u2018the linkages among the fair-flung international Chinese community\u2019, thereby incorporating Singapore and overseas Chinese communities in their usage of the term (Harding 1993, 660; also see Wang 1993).}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harding|first=Harry|date=December 1993|title=The Concept of \"Greater China\": Themes, Variations and Reservations*|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/china-quarterly/article/concept-of-greater-china-themes-variations-and-reservations/FAED34F84F7A8CF25CB3328991218293|journal=The China Quarterly|language=en|volume=136|pages=660\u2013686|doi=10.1017/S030574100003229X|issn=1468-2648|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\n\n===Commercial usage===\n\n[[Multinational corporation|Multinational corporations]] frequently use the term to name their regional [[Corporate headquarters|headquarters]]. For example, [[Procter & Gamble|P&G]] uses it to name its regional headquarter in [[Guangzhou]] that also operates in Hong Kong and [[Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web |title=P&G in Greater China |url=https://www.pgcareers.com/location-greaterchina |website=www.pgcareers.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] uses it for its regional headquarter in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news |title=Isabel Ge Mahe named Apple's managing director of Greater China |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/07/isabel-ge-mahe-named-apple-managing-director-of-greater-china/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Apple Newsroom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mickle |first1=Andrew Dowell and Tripp |title=Apple Closes All Its Stores Outside China Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-closes-all-its-stores-outside-china-over-coronavirus-11584172214 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Academic usage===\n\n[[Universities]] among other [[research institutions]] such as [[Columbia University]] use the term for studies of the region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater China - Weatherhead East Asian Institute |url=http://weai.columbia.edu/research/regions/china-region/ |website=weai.columbia.edu |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Political usage===\nThe term is often used to avoid invoking sensitivities over the [[political status of Taiwan]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\"/>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nFormer [[PRC Foreign Minister|Foreign Minister of China]] [[Wu Xueqian]] claimed in 1995 that China rejects the idea of a \"Greater China economic circle\" as it would never resort to economic expansionism or be involved in dividing the world.<ref name=\"He2001\">{{cite book|author=Henry Yuhuai He|title=Dictionary of the Political Thought of the People's Republic Of China|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=O6ac30QVU-4C&pg=PA48|accessdate=1 December 2012|year=2001|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-0569-6|pages=48\u2013}}</ref>\n\nMany Taiwanese don't believe themselves to be a part of greater China as it gives impression that Taiwan is part of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan Business TOPICS 2018\">{{cite web | title=Does Taiwan Belong In \"Greater China?\" | website=Taiwan Business TOPICS | date=2018-05-16 | url=https://topics.amcham.com.tw/2018/05/does-taiwan-belong-in-greater-china/ | access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"JSTOR\">{{cite journal | jstor=2620593 | title=China and Taiwan: Not Yet 'Greater China' | last1=Crane | first1=George T. | journal=International Affairs (Royal Institute of International Affairs 1944-) | year=1993 | volume=69 | issue=4 | pages=705\u2013723 }}</ref><ref name=\"National Sun Yat-Sen University\">{{cite web | author=Jeanette Ka-yee Yuen | title=The Myth of Greater China? Hong Kong as a prototype of Taiwan for Unification | website=Taiwan in Comparative Perspective | date=2020-03-22 | url=http://archive.is/Jgq9F | access-date=2020-03-22 | issn=1752-7732 |  others=Taiwan Research Programme, London School of Economics}}</ref>\n\nFor some Asians{{who|date=March 2020}}, the term is a reminder of the \"[[Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere]]\", a euphemism for the region controlled by [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japan]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite journal\n  | last = Shambaugh\n  | first = David\n  | title = Introduction: The Emergence of 'Greater China'\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 654\n  | date = December 1993}}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\n<!--[[File:China Proper 1944.png|thumb|left|250px|The map of \"China\" in the 1944 American [[propaganda film]] ''[[The Battle of China]]'', distinguishing \"[[China proper]]\" from [[Manchuria]], \"Mongolia\" (here [[Pan-Mongolism|Greater Mongolia]] including [[Mongolia|the present country]], the [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], and [[Tuva]]), [[Xinjiang|Sinkiang]], and [[Tibet]].]]\nThe term has been used for a long time, but with differing scope and connotations.-->\n\nIn the 1930s [[George Cressey]] used it to refer to the entire [[Qing Dynasty|Chinese Empire]], as opposed to [[China proper]].<ref name=\"Harding\">{{cite journal\n  | first = Harry\n  | last = Harding\n  | title = The Concept of 'Greater China': Themes, Variations and Reservations\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 660\u2013686\n  | date = December 1993| volume = 136\n | doi = 10.1017/S030574100003229X\n }}\n</ref> Usage by the United States on government maps in the 1940s as a political term included territories [[History of the Republic of China|claimed by the Republic of China]] that were part of the previous empire, or geographically to refer to topographical features associated with China that may or may not have lain entirely within Chinese political borders.<ref name=\"Harding\" /> \n\nThe concept began to appear again in Chinese-language sources in the late 1970s, referring the growing commercial ties between the mainland and Hong Kong, with the possibility of extending these to Taiwan, with perhaps the first such reference being in a Taiwanese journal ''Changqiao'' in 1979.<ref name=\"Harding\" />{{verification needed|date=March 2020}} \n\nThe English term subsequently re-emerged in the 1980s to refer to the growing economic ties between the regions as well as the possibility of political unification.<ref name=\"Harding\" /> It is not an institutionalized entity such as the [[European Union|EU]] or [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]]. The concept is a generalization to group several markets seen to be closely linked economically and does not imply [[sovereignty]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\">{{cite book  | first = Tilman  | last = Aretz  | title = The greater China factbook  | publisher = Taiwan Elite Press  | location = Taipei  | year = 2007  | url = http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | isbn = 978-986-7762-97-9 <!--9867762975-->  | oclc = 264977502  | url-status = live  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090131200221/http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | archivedate = 2009-01-31  }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Hong Kong|Taiwan|Singapore}}\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Adoption of Chinese literary culture]]\n* [[Bamboo network]]\n* [[East Asian cultural sphere]]\n* [[History of China]]\n* [[List of tributaries of China]]\n* [[Nine-dash line]]\n* [[Sinophone]]\n* [[Greater India]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese nationalism]]\n[[Category:Country classifications|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Cross-Strait relations]]\n[[Category:Cultural regions|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Geography of China]]\n[[Category:Historical regions]]\n", "name_user": "LiuJiageng", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greater_China"}
{"title_page": "Universidad La Salle", "text_new": "{{short description|University}}\n{{other uses|La Salle University (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name         = Universidad La Salle\n| image        = La salle mx logo.png\n| image_size   = 145px\n| motto        = ''Indivisa Manent'' ([[Latin]])\n| mottoeng     = Remain Undivided\n| established  = 1962 (see [[#History|history]])\n| type         = [[Private university|Private]]\n| affiliation  = [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] ([[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools|Lasallian]])\n| president    = Enrique Gonz\u00e1lez \u00c1lvarez\n| city         = [[Mexico City]]\n| state        = [[Mexican Federal District|Distrito Federal]]\n| country      = [[M\u00e9xico]]\n| nickname     = \u00c1guilas De La Salle\n| colors       = [[Blue]], [[white]] and [[red]]\n| affiliations = [[Consortium for North American Higher Education Collaboration|CNAHEC]]<br>[http://www.lasalle-ialu.org/ IALU]\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.ulsa.edu.mx/}}\n}}\n'''Universidad La Salle''' (ULSA) is a private institution of higher education with 15 campuses in [[Mexico]]. It is part of the [[Institute of the Brothers of the Christian Schools]]. It offers [[High school diploma|high school]], [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor]], [[Master's degree|master]] and [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]] degrees. It has had an expansion in the country, creating its own university national system. Its main campus is located in [[Mexico City]], and has a presence in [[Ciudad Obreg\u00f3n]], [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]], [[Gomez Palacio]], [[Monterrey]], [[Ciudad Victoria]], [[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Leon]], [[Morelia]], [[Pachuca]], [[Ciudad Nezahualc\u00f3yotl]], [[Cuernavaca]], [[Puebla]], [[Oaxaca]], [[Cancun]] and [[Saltillo]].\n\nIt is part of the educational community of the [[Brothers of the Christian Schools]], founded by Saint [[Jean-Baptiste de La Salle]], patron saint of education. The congregation has about seventy-seven thousand lay partners and one million students around the world, with establishments of higher learning in [[Argentina]], [[Belgium]], [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Ivory Coast]], [[Spain]], [[France]], [[Guatemala]], the [[Philippines]], the [[United States]], [[Venezuela]] and [[Israel]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1905, the brothers of La Salle Jerbert Alphonse Gibert, Adrien Marie Astruc, Amed\u00e9e Francois Vincent and Antoinde Claude Carrel traveled to Mexico from [[Le Havre]], France, along with Br. Pedro Celestino Schniedier who traveled from Colombia. They founded the delegation of LaSalle brethren in Mexico. The brothers created schools in Puebla, Toluca, Torreon, Monterrey, and various other locations in the country. Their first high school in Mexico City opened in 1931, the Colegio Franc\u00e9s De la Salle. In 1932 the school won formal recognition and authorization by the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]]. In 1938 the Colegio Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n was also established in the Colonia San Rafael.\n\nThe history of Universidad La Salle began with the relocation of Colegio Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n to the center of the traditional Colonia Condesa in Mexico City in 1962. On February 15 it opened its doors with only the high school building completed and a partially built tower, gym and auditorium. By May of the same year, it had rapidly grown enough to announce its transformation from a just a school to a full university category. Since then it has undergone continuous expansion. The main campus has a population of approximately 10,000 students, and has expanded its campus throughout Mexico City with buildings in many areas of the city.\n\nThere are branches of Universidad La Salle in 15 Mexican states. The La Salle educational institution itself is represented in over 82 different countries, and 5 continents making it the largest educational community in the world.\n\nULSA is among the top 7 private universities in Mexico and ranked in the top three in areas such as Architecture, Mechanical Engineering, Industrial Engineering, Chemical Engineering and Medicine.\n\nThe Universidad La Salle medical school (Facultad Mexicana de Medicina) is one of the most prestigious universities in Mexico for medical training. It was Mexico's first private medical school and was founded in 1970. It is accredited by the Consejo Mexicano para la Acreditaci\u00f3n de la Educaci\u00f3n M\u00e9dica (COMAEM), and is listed in the International Medical Education Directory. Albeit a young school, many of the country's department heads are graduates from La Salle.\n[[File:Murayl y tempusfugit.jpg|thumb|200px]]\n\n==University presidents==\n*2011\u2013Present Dr. Enrique Gonzalez Alvarez\n*2009\u20132011 M.A. Mart\u00edn Rocha Pedrajo\n*2006\u20132009 [[Doctor (title)|Dr.]] Ambrosio Luna Salas\n*2000\u20132006 [[Master (college)|Mtro.]] Ra\u00fal Valadez Garc\u00eda\n*1991\u20132000 Dr. Lucio Tazzer de Schrijver\n*1988\u20131991 Dr. Jos\u00e9 Cervantes Hern\u00e1ndez\n*1983\u20131988 M.A. C\u00e9sar Rangel Barrera\n*1974\u20131983 Dr. Francisco L. Cervantes Lechuga\n*1968\u20131974 Dr. Guillermo Alba L\u00f3pez\n*1962\u20131968 Dr. Manuel de J. \u00c1lvarez Campos\n\n==Campuses==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Canc\u00fan]]\n*[[La Salle University of Chihuahua|Chihuahua]]\n*[[Ciudad Obreg\u00f3n]]\n*[[Ciudad Nezahualc\u00f3yotl]]\n*[[Ciudad Victoria]]\n*[[Cuernavaca]]\n*[[Guadalajara, Jalisco|Guadalajara]]\n*[[Comarca Lagunera|Laguna]]\n*[[Le\u00f3n, Guanajuato|Le\u00f3n]]\n*[[Mexico City]]\n*[[Monterrey]]\n*[[Morelia]]\n*[[Pachuca]]\n*[[Puebla, Puebla|Puebla]]\n*[[Saltillo]]\n*[[Oaxaca]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Programs==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Architecture]]\n*[[Accounting]]\n*[[Biomedical Engineering]]\n*[[Business Administration]]\n*[[Chemical engineering]]\n*[[Chemistry]] of [[Food]]\n*[[Civil engineering]]\n*[[Communication studies|Communications]]\n*[[Cybernetics]] and [[computer science]] engineering\n*[[Education]]\n*[[Electrical engineering|Electrical]] and [[electronics engineering|electronic systems engineering]]\n*[[Graphic design]]\n*[[Industrial engineering]]\n*[[International Relations]]\n*[[international trade|International business trade]]\n*[[Law school|Law]]\n*[[Marketing]]\n*[[Management information systems]]\n*[[Mechanical engineering|Mechanical]] and [[Energy]] systems engineering\n*[[Mechatronics Engineering]]\n*[[Medicine]]\n*[[Pharmaceutical]] [[biochemistry]]\n*[[Philosophy]]\n*[[Religious studies]]\n*[[University-preparatory school]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Degrees==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"background:#DDEEFF;\"\n!align=\"center\"|Foundation Year\n!align=\"center\"|School\n!align=\"center\"|Career\n!align=\"center\"|Starting Year\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1962\n|align=\"center\"|High School\n|align=\"left\"|\n|align=\"center\"|1962\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1964\n|align=\"center\"|Mexican School of Architecture, Design and Communication\n|align=\"left\"|Architecture\n|align=\"center\"|1964\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|Communication Science\n|align=\"center\"|2001\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|Graphic Design\n|align=\"center\"|1990\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1961\n|align=\"center\"|Business School\n|align=\"left\"|Actuar\u00eda\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|Administration\n|align=\"center\"|1961\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|Trade and International Business\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|Accounts\n|align=\"center\"|1961\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|Information Technology for Business\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1967\n|align=\"center\"|Faculty of Law\n|align=\"left\"|Law\n|align=\"center\"|1967\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"center\"|\n|align=\"left\"|International Relationships\n|align=\"center\"|\n|-\n|align=\"center\"|1968\n|align=\"center\"|Fa